Here is a problem from Griffith's book Introduction to E&M . Let $\theta(x)$ be the step function $$\theta(x) = \begin{cases}
0, & x \le 0, \\
1, & x \gt 0. 
\end{cases}
$$ The question is how to prove $\frac{d\theta}{dx} = \delta(x)$ . I think since the function is discontinuous at $x = 0$ , there is no definition of $\frac{d\theta}{dx}$ at the point $x = 0$ at all. Thus, how could we show the equivalence of a equation if the left part of equation is not defined at the point $x = 0$ ?
